atue -- tPart IV Reflections -- tHow I Came to Criticize Nagai Takashi's Urakami Holocaust Theory -- tOn Rereleasing The Bells of Nagasaki to the World -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA critical introduction to how the Nagasaki atomic bombing has been remembered, especially in contrast to that of Hiroshima.In the decades following the atomic bombing of Nagasaki on August 9, 1945, the city’s residents processed their trauma and formed narratives of the destruction and reconstruction in ways that reflected their regional history and social makeup. In doing so, they created a multi-layered urban identity as an atomic-bombed city that differed markedly from Hiroshima’s image. Shadows of Nagasaki traces how Nagasaki’s trauma, history, and memory of the bombing manifested through some of the city’s many post-atomic memoryscapes, such as literature, religious discourse, art, historical landmarks, commemorative spaces, and architecture. In addition, the book pays particular attention to how the city’s history of international culture, exemplified best perhaps by the region’s Christian (especially Catholic) past, informed its response to the atomic trauma and shaped its postwar urban identity. Key historical actors in the volume’s chapters include writers, Japanese- Catholic leaders, atomic-bombing survivors (known as hibakusha), municipal officials, American occupation personnel, peace activists, artists, and architects. The story of how these diverse groups of people processed and participated in the discourse surrounding the legacies of Nagasaki’s bomb­ing shows how regional history, culture, and politics—rather than national ones—become the most influential factors shaping narratives of destruction and reconstruction after mass trauma. In turn, and especially in the case of urban destruction, new identities emerge and old ones are rekindled, not to serve national politics or social interests but to bolster narratives that reflect local circumstances.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aHistory. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aReligion. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh  aAtomic bombing.  aCatholicism.  aChristianity.  aHibakusha.  aJapanese Literature.  aMemory.  aNagasaki.  aRuins.  aTrauma.1 aBurke-Gaffney, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiehl, Chad R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiehl, Chad R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGasha, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaynes, Anthony Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMason, Michele M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcClelland, Gwyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNagai, Tokusaburō, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNakao, Maika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPark, Haeseong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRausch, Franklin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShirokawa, Nanase, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTakahashi, Shinji, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYasuda, Anri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075168040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781531504984?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781531504984423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isb